# Flux git auth — the GitHub App, installed per org

Flux authenticates to GitHub with a **GitHub App**, never a PAT (invariant 4).
The reality that bites people: **one App, installed separately on every org**
whose repos Flux must read — each install has its own **installation ID**, and
Flux needs **one secret per org** (same private key, that org's installation
ID). These are **infrastructure credentials**: created directly in the cluster,
**never committed, not even sealed** (invariant 3).

## The App (once per instance)

Create **one** GitHub App for the whole instance, named `Server
{{ community_name }}` (or `Server <org>`):

- **Permissions:** Repository → Contents: **Read-only** (Flux only reads). If
  an app uses Flux image-automation that writes tag bumps back into this repo,
  also grant Contents: **Read and write** — but prefer the app-CI-commits-the-tag
  pattern (`patterns/app-deploy-ci/`) which needs no write.
- **Where can this App be installed:** Any account (so it can be installed on
  every org that hosts repos Flux reads).
- Note the **App ID** and generate a **private key** (`.pem`). The key is
  shared across every installation.

## Install on each org

Install the App on **every** org whose repos a `GitRepository` points at —
this repo's org (`{{ github_owner }}`) and any org hosting an app overlay Flux
pulls. Each installation gets a distinct installation ID.

Find an org's installation ID (App ID is the same everywhere):

```bash
gh api /orgs/<org>/installations \
  --jq '.installations[] | select(.app_id==<app-id>) | .id'
```

For a user account rather than an org, use `/users/<user>/installation` (the
single installation for that account):

```bash
gh api /users/<user>/installation --jq '.id'
```

## One Flux secret per org (in the cluster, never in git)

For each org, create a secret holding the **App ID**, **that org's
installation ID**, and the **shared private key**:

```bash
kubectl create secret generic <org>-flux-secret -n flux-system \
  --from-literal=githubAppID=<app-id> \
  --from-literal=githubAppInstallationID=<installation-id> \
  --from-file=githubAppPrivateKey=<app-key.pem>
```

Do this for `{{ github_owner }}` (this repo's org) and once more for every
other org Flux reads — same `<app-id>` and same `.pem`, only the installation
ID differs.

## Reference it from the GitRepository

Each `GitRepository` whose repo lives in `<org>` uses `provider: github` and
points at that org's secret:

```yaml
spec:
  provider: github
  secretRef:
    name: <org>-flux-secret
```

For this repo's root sync, this is already wired in `flux/gotk-sync.yaml`
(uncomment the `secretRef`). `scripts/new-app.sh` writes the matching
`provider`/`secretRef` for an app whose overlay lives in another org — make
sure that org's `<org>-flux-secret` exists in the cluster first, or the
`GitRepository` reports an auth error.

## Verify

```bash
flux get sources git -A    # all Ready=True; none "authentication required"
```

## Rebuild note (accepted trade-off)

Because these secrets are never in git (invariant 3), they are **not**
reproducible from the repo. On a cluster rebuild, recreate every
`<org>-flux-secret` by hand with the commands above (App ID + per-org
installation ID + the shared `.pem`). Keep the `.pem` and App ID in the
operator's password manager, not in this repo.
